column6: What year did you complete your clinical training?
column10: How many years have you been at Maniilaq (use 0 if less than one year)?
column11: Have you worked at another site within the ATHS?
column12: Have you been employed clinically (not just during training) in another rural setting?
column13: Question 1: Available vitals     HR   BP     120   130/80       Experienced health aid calls you to say she is at the scene of a snowmachine accident just outside the village where a 38 YO male was driving a snowmachine at an unknown rate of speed and wrecked it. He ended up 15' from the snow machine which is buried in a snowdrift. He didn't have a helmet on. He is still unconscious with apparent swelling on right side of face and a laceration over brow. He is breathing on his own, vitals as above. He withdraws to painful stimuli. No witness and no other history available. He doesn't smell of ETOH. They are putting in c-collar and transporting back to clinic. What do you want to do?
column14: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column15: Question 2:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     90   18   99   135/80   98.5     You receive a call from an inexperienced health aide in the clinic who sounds concerned over a patient with a stab wound to the abdomen. The patient says he was drinking earlier but is sobering now and while can't tell you much about the incident he points to a laceration to the left side of his abdomen. After getting him undressed there is no area of tenderness or other signs of trauma outside of the abdomen, full trauma survey otherwise negative. He has no abdominal tenderness. The health aide takes a closer look at the injury and probes with a soft tipped swap without any evidence of deeper space injury. You review of the photos sent in the chart and he appears to have a 3cm superficial laceration to the abdomen. The health aide wants to know what to do next.
column16: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column17: Question 3:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     105   10   92   132/78   97.8     37 YO female is found down outside by a child walking home from school for lunch. There was an empty alcohol bottle nearby and she is by herself. No signs of struggle and she's dressed with jacket on even though it's summer and weather is clear. Health aids bring her to the clinic and she is moaning, incoherent, but breathing on her own, although sometimes needs a sternal rub to respond. She isn't following directions. They get her out of her clothes and both primary and secondary survey don't identify areas of trauma. Blood sugar is 91. She hasn't been able to provide a pregnancy test, and chart doesn't suggest recent visits.
column18: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column19: Question 4:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     200   80   92   --   101.2 rectal     You receive a call from a new health aide overnight about a 4mo ex-full term baby with respiratory distress. Mother reports this is the 3rd day of an illness involving sneezing, coughing, rhinorrhea and fevers. Several other siblings with similar symptoms with numerous other children in village recently diagnosed with RSV. This evening family noticed she was unable to breastfeed due to her 'breathing funny.' Health aide says that she is breathing fast with intercostal retractions, nasal flaring, tracheal tugging and diffuse wheeze throughout her lungs. FSBS 92. After saline neb and acetaminophen in clinic, child remains with intercostal retractions with desaturations to 85% while sleeping.
column20: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column21: Question 5:  No vitals obtained.  7 YO male was riding on the back of his older brother's 4-wheeler when as they were slowing down in front of the school the younger brother jumped off and tumbled, when he got up he says his left wrist hurt. A teacher saw the event happen and estimates they were only going 5-10 MPH. There is no other injuries to child who complains of pain at left wrist. Health aids do an exam and can't find any swelling or specific areas that are tender, including anatomic snuffbox (nontender). He is able to use his wrist well and has full ROM but mom wants an Xray because she thinks it's broken.
column22: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column23: Question 6:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     105   24   91   135/70   100.6     Health aide calls overnight for a 73yoF PMH COPD, HTN, NIDDM, mild CHF, and renal disease who has had breathing difficulties that have worsened over the past week. He was seen in clinic 2days prior for cough, chills and runny nose. In reviewing his chart of the previous visit his lungs had a mild wheeze which improved with duoneb in clinic after which he was sent home with a steroid burst and instructions for home albuterol use. This evening he was having worsening cough, shortness of breath and right sided chest pain worse with coughing. Health aide notes that he now has focal crackles to the right lower lobe as well as diffuse wheeze throughout. His EKG is normal. After acetaminophen and duonebx2 her wheezing and chest pain have improved a little, although crackles remain. The health aide asks if you want to give any other medications and what the next steps should be.
column24: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column25: Question 7: Available vitals:     Temp     101.8     A young mother has just brought her 12-day old infant in after he was being fussy at home and found to have a temp to 101.8 rectal. He hasn't had any other symptoms, but his older sister is in pre-school and has been sick too. The patient's prenatal course notable for full term delivery that was GBS + and inadequately treated during labor, but no other concerning information in chart. By history and physical of health aids, he seems to be dehydrated with only 2 diapers in last 24 hours and decreased feeding. There is no rash and no cough. Blood sugar is normal. CHA thinks he looks sick, and you do a video interview and agree.
column26: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column27: Question 8:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     140   30   98   90/50   102.4 rectal     You get a phone call from a worried health aide who is waiting for a family who is running over with a child they think had a seizure. You do a quick review of the chart and find an otherwise health 19 month with up to date vaccinations. The health aide calls back and tells you he has been sick with runny nose, cough, decreased appetite over the past 2days, similar to other children in the household. This evening after eating dinner his family saw him eyes open, generalized body shaking for ~3min. Afterwards he was minimally responsive and now in clinic appearing to start acting normally. FSBS normal. After rectal Tylenol and watching the child for approximately 2hrs he is awake, playful and sipping on juice in clinic. The rest of his repeat vitals are normal too.
column28: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column29: Question 9:  No vitals obtained.  It's the middle of the night and a 60 YO female neighbor of the health aide has come in looking sick with fever, tachycardia, and dysuria. She has a history of renal impairment and diabetes. A UA is consistent with UTI as source. You decide to medevac her. unfortunately, it's now dark and the village airport lights are out and medevac won't go during nighttime hours. Your health aid is able to give her 2 liters of IVF and a dose of ceftriaxone. On recheck your patient has normal vital signs and is tolerating orals. It's now approaching daybreak and your medevac is calling to know if they should launch or not, what do you tell them?
column30: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column31: Question 10:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     130   22   99   110/70   100.6     Family called the health aide on call for worsening abdominal pain in their 7-year-old son. Symptoms started yesterday with some decreased appetite and vague abdominal pain. This evening he had been unable to eat anything, lying in bed and crying. He had a single episode of vomiting. On exam the health aide localizes the pain to the right lower quadrant with +psoas sign, unable to assess rebound tenderness as the child is crying and pushing away her hands.
column32: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column33: Question 11:  No vitals obtained.  A 48 YO female comes complaining of RUQ and epigastric pain in the setting of prior episodes. While the health aids are doing their history and physical you review the chart. This patient has had an ultrasound for similar presentation one month ago at which time she was seen by surgery for possible gallbladder disease. The US showed no stones, sludge, or gallbladder abnormalities, and on further review surgeon thought that this most likely caused by GERD. The health aids find out that she had been good about taking her PPI and diet and that has helped, but there was a family gathering in town and she drank for a couple of days before these symptoms started. She has no nausea or vomiting and is tolerating POs in clinic. Her vitals are reassuring. An exam does show both epigastric and RUQ tenderness but no rebound or guarding. You review your institutions strategy for treating GERD for a 2 month trial of PPIs, which she would be in the middle of given no previous or current alarm symptoms.
column34: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column35: Question 12:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     90   18   99   125/80   98.1     21yoF G1P0 (EGA 30weeks) presenting to the clinic for suprapubic abdominal cramping. Over the past 2 days she has had intermittent worsening 'contraction like pain'. She does not have burning with urination or vaginal bleeding. Her urinalysis is without evidence of infection. Today the symptoms are coming every 30minutes. You give a liter of IVF and a dose of nifedpine. An hour later she no longer has symptoms.
column36: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column37: Question 13:     HR   BP     110   105/71     32 YO G4P2 with acute onset pelvic pain and vaginal bleeding now comes into village clinic with a new positive pregnancy test. Her LMP puts current pregnancy at about 7 weeks. Health aides report no prior care in current pregnancy, active vaginal bleeding, a HR of 110 and BP is 105/71. She feels dizzy when she stands up and has abdominal tenderness on exam.
column38: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column39: Question 14:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     80   18   99   120/80   98.2     16yoM without medical history who is brought in by older sister for redness to his left leg. He was out at fish camp for the past week where he scraped his leg on a loose wooden board. Over the past 2days he has had worsening pain and redness around the wound. When he returned today his sister brought him to clinic. On reviewing photos sent by the health aide you see he has a 3cm superficial laceration with minimal purulence to his right inner shin with mild streaking into inner thigh. Health aide reports normal pulses, sensation, and mildly tender inguinal lymph nodes. Tetanus is up to date.
column40: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column41: Question 15: No vitals obtained.  13 YO female brought in by mother for concern of Tylenol overdose about 6 hours prior. Happened when child got home from school and mom worked late. When she got home, child told mom what she had done. Mom brings in the Tylenol bottle that she says she got the pills from and it's still mostly full. Child says she took about '10' tabs of 500 mg acetaminophen. She has no abdominal pain, nausea, or vomiting. You and health aids consult with poison control and start her on oral NAC while in village. Childs vitals are normal and poison control recommends not starting activated charcoal given time elapsed since ingestion.
column42: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column43: Question 16:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     101   15   98   125/83   98.6     37 YO G5P3 at 38 weeks by good dating comes into village clinic with contractions. The CHAP calls you and says her water broke 2 hours ago and contractions less than 5 minutes apart since then. More help is on the way with 2 other CHAPs. Additionally, she has prior history of village delivery and CHAPs have been contacting her to go to regional hub to await delivery there, but she has been reticent to do so. No prior complications with other deliveries. FHT 145 and contractions palpate about 2-3 minutes.
column44: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column45: Question 17:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     0   0   0   0   Not done     Called by health aid from patient home with CPR in progress on 58 YO male who was found down inside the home by a family member who had just left the room for a brief period. Patient had some nausea develop during the day and felt tired, but no other prior symptoms and no history of DNR/I noted. They tell you that he had high blood pressure and cholesterol and was good about taking his medications. CHAP brought an AED that has already been hooked up. No shock advised, and no pulse or respiratory movement noted, but warm and no livido reticularis or rigor mortis. CPR ongoing by multiple responders you can hear in the background.
column46: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column47: Question 18:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     0   0   0   0   Not done     17 YO male was playing with his father's hunting rifle inside the house and shot himself through the chest and abdomen. His younger brother was in the room and saw the gun go off-it didn't hit anything else. He called his parents who called CHAP. When CHAP arrived, parents had already started CPR, but CHAP can't find a pulse and is a lone responder.
column48: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column49: Question 19:      HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     95   18   94   147/70   98.6     62 YO female with history of osteoporosis slipped and fell off her outside deck landing on ground about 4 feet below. She was unable to get up, has pain in her left groin and is having a hard time talking with the heath aides because it hurts so bad, although their assessment is she didn't hurt anything else and isn't confused or otherwise injured. Leg described as foreshortened and rotated and she won't tolerate movement. Health aides think they need to get her out of there.
column50: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
column51: Question 20:     HR   RR   SpO2   BP   Temp     183   26   97   Not done   99.0     16-month-old ex full term male infant with no significant past medical history comes into CHAP clinic brought in by two new parents who report 2 hours of non-stop crying. They are worried as his cry seems different and he hasn't ever cried this much. No fever, illness or other problems noted. He had normal appetite for breast milk as usual earlier in the day and same number of wet diapers, although now he's crying incessantly he doesn't seem to be comforted by breastfeeding. Exam completed; not consolable but doesn't seem to have bulging fontanel, red ears, delayed cap refill, belly seems maybe distended to health aid and she's a little worried that it's tender on exam but hard to tell. No BMs while in the clinic but he won't eat either. He did vomit non-bilious emesis x 1, looked like curdled breast milk. You try Tylenol as a temporizing measure
column52: How confident are you of this decision (10 being very confident, and 1 being not confident at all)
